Fake Airdrops & Wallet Drainers – Scammers often pose as legit projects, sending phishing links via fake Twitter accounts or Discord messages. Clicking them connects your wallet to a malicious contract, draining funds.

fields.experience:
A recent situation that stands out occurred in mid-March 2025, involving a trader on Uniswap V3, a prominent decentralized exchange in the Web3 ecosystem. Posts on X from users like @JustDeauIt and @TheDeFiPlug, dated March 12 and 13, 2025, respectively, highlight a case where a user lost over $216,000 in a single swap attempt. The trader intended to exchange $221,000 worth of USDC for USDT in a liquidity pool containing over $35 million in USDC and USDT—seemingly a safe, liquid environment. However, the transaction was exploited through a “sandwich attack,” a common unethical tactic in decentralized finance (DeFi).

Here’s what happened: An MEV (Maximal Extractable Value) bot detected the trader’s large pending swap in the Ethereum mempool. The bot front-ran the transaction by submitting a buy order with higher gas fees, purchasing USDT just before the trader’s swap executed, which drove up the price. After the trader’s swap completed at the inflated rate, the bot immediately sold the USDT back into the pool at a profit, effectively “sandwiching” the trader’s transaction. This left the trader with significantly less USDT than expected—resulting in a loss exceeding $200,000 across three related transactions, as detailed in on-chain analyses shared on X.

This incident exposes an unethical underbelly of Web3’s DeFi landscape: while decentralized platforms like Uniswap promise autonomy and transparency, they’re vulnerable to manipulation by sophisticated actors exploiting the system’s openness. Sandwich attacks aren’t outright scams but thrive in a regulatory gray area, leveraging Web3’s trustless nature against less-savvy users. The situation underscores a broader issue—despite billions in liquidity, DeFi remains a Wild West where technical exploits can drain funds instantly, often without recourse.
